Beyond search and JSON validation, expanding a local multi-agent system means transforming it from a text processor into a highly resilient, media-aware execution engine. Cloud platforms have massive pipelines built-in to parse files, render JavaScript, and manage high-latency operations.

To bridge this gap locally with Llama 3.2, you can integrate several technical layers into your architecture:

1. The Rendering & Deep Crawling Layer
A standard Python request script often breaks when trying to scrape modern, JavaScript-heavy Single Page Applications (SPAs) or sites protected by basic anti-bot scripts.

The Strategy: Upgrade your scraping infrastructure to support browser primitives like headless scrolling, session states, and lazy-loading.

The Tooling: Crawl4AI or Playwright. Crawl4AI is a popular, open-source, local-first LLM crawler built specifically on top of Playwright. It automatically strips out navigation chrome, cookie banners, and ads, feeding your downstream agents (like page_classifier.py) pre-cleaned Markdown, which saves thousands of local tokens.

2. Multi-Format Document Parsing (The PDF/Excel Layer)
Market intelligence often relies on parsing local PDF reports, quarterly earnings, and spreadsheets, not just raw web text. If an agent downloads a financial PDF or an investor deck, it needs to translate it into an LLM-readable format.

The Strategy: Implement a robust document processing tool that parses layout-heavy documents into clean text tables.

The Tooling: Microsoft's MarkItDown or PyMuPDF. Libraries like MarkItDown easily convert PDFs, Excel sheets, and Word docs straight into clean, structured Markdown, retaining tables and hierarchical heading structures that Llama 3.2 can easily interpret.

3. The Local Caching Layer (Compute & Cost Saver)
Local inference on Llama 3.2 takes time. If your orchestrator loops through multiple workflows or repeatedly tests the same dataset during debugging, you don't want to wait for the model to re-process identical prompts, nor do you want to get rate-limited by scraping identical URLs.

The Strategy: Implement an LLM Cache and a Web Request Cache.

The Tooling: Use a simple key-value store or a local library like diskcache or SQLite. Before the orchestrator hands a text block to sentiment_analysis.py, it calculates a quick hash of the prompt. If that hash exists in the local database, it returns the stored analysis instantly instead of running model inference again.

4. Self-Correction & Reflection Loop
Small local models can make mistakes on the first try—they might hallucinate a JSON key, miss an entity extraction, or try to visit a broken URL.

The Strategy: Give the agent a "Review" step before finishing a task.

The Flow:

Agent Executes: Tries to extract companies using ner_agent.py.

Validator Checks: Notices the output array is empty or structurally broken.

Reflection Trigger: The system automatically passes the output back to the agent with a prompt like: "Your previous output failed validation due to X. Please fix the formatting and try again." Give the agent up to 2-3 retries before falling back to a safe default.

5. Asynchronous Parallel Workers
If your link_extractor.py finds 5 relevant URLs to analyze, processing them sequentially will cause massive bottlenecks in your application flow.

The Strategy: Transition the orchestrator pipeline to handle asynchronous task execution.

The Tooling: Python's built-in asyncio or a lightweight task worker queue. This allows your orchestrator to blast out requests to web_scraper.py for all 5 URLs concurrently, gather the results onto your shared state "blackboard," and then sequentially pass the structured data to Llama 3.2.

